Functions Used in My Sixth SQL Project

TRIM

What it does
TRIM removes extra spaces from the beginning and end of text values.
Why it was used
Many datasets contain hidden spaces that users accidentally type when entering information. These spaces make values appear identical but SQL treats them as different entries. Removing these spaces makes the data consistent and prevents issues when filtering or grouping text values.

ISNULL

What it does
ISNULL replaces missing values (NULL values) with another value that you choose.
Why it was used
Datasets often contain missing information. Instead of leaving empty values, they were replaced with 0 so calculations and results remain readable and easier to analyze.

NULLIF

What it does
NULLIF compares two values and returns NULL if they are equal.
Why it was used
It was used as a safety measure to prevent divide-by-zero errors. If a value that would cause a division problem appears, it converts that value to NULL so the calculation does not crash.

CEILING

What it does
CEILING rounds a number up to the nearest whole number.

Why it was used
Some numerical values may contain decimals that are not needed. Rounding up ensures the result becomes a clean whole number.
Example concept:
10.1 becomes 11
10.9 becomes 11

SUM

What it does
SUM adds together every value in a column to produce a total.
Why it was used
This function allows the dataset to calculate totals such as the overall value of a column. It is commonly used in analytics when calculating totals like income, revenue, or scores.

COALESCE

What it does
COALESCE returns the first value that is not NULL from a list of values.
Why it was used
Sometimes data may contain missing values. This function ensures that if the first value is missing, SQL automatically selects the next available value instead.
It is useful for making sure queries still return usable data.

ABS

What it does
ABS converts negative numbers into positive numbers.
Why it was used
This function shows the distance of a number from zero, ignoring whether the number was positive or negative.
Example concept:
-10 becomes 10
10 stays 10
This is useful when measuring differences between numbers.

STRING_AGG

What it does
STRING_AGG combines values from multiple rows into one single text string, separated by a chosen character.
Why it was used
This allows many row values to be merged together into a readable list instead of appearing on separate rows.
This is useful for summaries or creating compact reports.

CAST

What it does
CAST converts one datatype into another datatype.
Why it was used
It was used to convert numeric values into text so they could be combined into a long string. This also bypasses SQL’s default character length limit when aggregating large text results.

ROW_NUMBER
What it does
ROW_NUMBER assigns a unique number to each row in a result set.
Why it was used
This creates a row counter that can rank or organize rows based on a condition such as highest income or another sorted column.
It is often used for ranking, pagination, or identifying row order.

OVER

What it does
OVER defines the set of rows that a window function should operate on.
Why it was used
Some functions need to look at multiple rows instead of just one row. The OVER clause tells SQL how those rows should be grouped or ordered for the calculation.
It is commonly used with ranking and comparison functions.

LAG

What it does
LAG retrieves a value from the previous row in a dataset.
Why it was used
This allows comparisons between rows. For example, you can compare the current value with the previous value to detect increases, decreases, or trends.
This is commonly used in financial analysis and trend tracking.

